Forecasting New Policy Counts using the MMM ETS model

Brittany Fuzia

3/14/19

This code uses the posterior distributions of the smoothing parameters from the MMM model to forecast the New Policy Counts time series

Load NPC data

dnpc <- read.csv("New Policy Count.csv", sep = "\t")
dnpc <- dnpc[,1:3] #get rid of cols
names(dnpc) <- c("t", "date", "y") #name cols
dnpc <- subset(dnpc, !is.na(y)) #get rid of nans (missing data for most recent months)
dnpc$y <-  dnpc$y/1e3 #make smaller
dnpc$date <- as.Date(dnpc$date, '%m/%d/%Y')
yts <- ts(dnpc$y, start=c(2011,1), frequency=12) #turn into time series class

Fit with the ETS package, to compare with the results from Stan

Using all data and data up until Apr 2018

etsfit <- ets(yts,model='MMM')
etsfit_apr18 <- ets(ts(dnpc$y[1:88], start=c(2011,1), frequency=12),model='MMM')

#View(paramdf)

Use draws from the posterior to predict future policy counts

sim_mmm <- function(modsim, h = 12, numsim = length(modsim$alpha), seed = NULL){
  
  stopifnot(numsim <= length(modsim$alpha)) #if you set numsim, make sure it doesn't want more data than is there
  latestj <- ncol(modsim$l) #get index of last data point
  seasonality_num <- 12 #how many periods per season
  
  #get the samples for each parameter
  alpha <- modsim$alpha[1:numsim] 
  gamma <- modsim$gamma[1:numsim]
  beta <- modsim$beta[1:numsim]
  sigma <- modsim$sigma[1:numsim]
  l <- modsim$l[1:numsim, latestj]
  b <- modsim$b[1:numsim, latestj]
  s <- modsim$s[1:numsim, (latestj - seasonality_num + 1):latestj] #get last 12 periods

  #simulate random noise, gaussian with mean zero and std from fit
  if(!is.null(seed)) set.seed(seed)
  epsilon <- matrix(rnorm(n = h * numsim, mean = 0, sd = sigma), nrow = numsim) 
  
  #create arrays to store the states
  bnew  <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  snew  <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  lnew  <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  munew <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  
  #how the states depend on the smoothing parameters and noise
  #calculate first forecasted point using the last states from the chains
  bnew[,1] <- b * (1 + beta * epsilon[,1])
  snew[,1] <- s[,1] * (1 + gamma * epsilon[,1])
  lnew[,1] <- l * b * (1 + alpha * epsilon[,1])
  munew[,1] <- l*b*s[,1]
    
  #propagate forward
  for(i in 2:h){
    bnew[,i] <- bnew[,i-1] * (1 + beta * epsilon[,i])
    if(i <= seasonality_num){
      snew[,i] <- s[,i]  * (1 + gamma * epsilon[,i])
      munew[,i] <- lnew[,i-1] * bnew[,i-1] * s[,i]
    }else{
      snew[,i] <- snew[,i - seasonality_num]  * (1 + gamma * epsilon[,i])
      munew[,i] <- lnew[,i-1] * bnew[,i-1] * snew[,i - seasonality_num]
    }
    lnew[,i] <- lnew[,i-1] * bnew[,i-1] * (1 + alpha * epsilon[,i])
  }

  ynew <- munew*(1+epsilon)
  return(list(munew = munew, ynew = ynew))
}


#Same forecast, but with fixed smoothing parameters, the only thing changing is the random noise
sim_mmm_fixedparam <- function(modsim, h = 12, alpha=alphaets, beta=betaets, gamma=gammaets, sigma=sigmaets, numsim = length(modsim$alpha), seed = NULL){
  stopifnot(numsim <= length(modsim$alpha))
  latestj <- ncol(modsim$l)
  seasonality_num <- 12
  l <- modsim$l[1:numsim, latestj]
  b <- modsim$b[1:numsim, latestj]
  s <- modsim$s[1:numsim, (latestj - seasonality_num + 1):latestj]

  if(!is.null(seed)) set.seed(seed)
  epsilon <- matrix(rnorm(n = h * numsim, mean = 0, sd = sigma), nrow = numsim)
  bnew  <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  snew  <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  lnew  <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  munew <- matrix(rep(NA_real_, h * numsim), nrow = numsim)
  
  bnew[,1] <- b * (1 + beta * epsilon[,1])
  snew[,1] <- s[,1] * (1 + gamma * epsilon[,1])
  lnew[,1] <- l * b * (1 + alpha * epsilon[,1])
  munew[,1] <- l*b*s[,1]
    
  for(i in 2:h){
    bnew[,i] <- bnew[,i-1] * (1 + beta * epsilon[,i])
    if(i <= seasonality_num){
      snew[,i] <- s[,i]  * (1 + gamma * epsilon[,i])
      munew[,i] <- lnew[,i-1] * bnew[,i-1] * s[,i]
    }else{
      snew[,i] <- snew[,i - seasonality_num]  * (1 + gamma * epsilon[,i])
      munew[,i] <- lnew[,i-1] * bnew[,i-1] * snew[,i - seasonality_num]
    }
    lnew[,i] <- lnew[,i-1] * bnew[,i-1] * (1 + alpha * epsilon[,i])
  }

  ynew <- munew*(1+epsilon)
  return(list(munew = munew, ynew = ynew))
}

orig_npc <- data.table( #original data, for plotting
  data='Data through Dec 2018',

  ymax=NA_real_
)

    data = 'ets (starting Jan 2019)',

    ymax =  as.numeric(etspred$upper) * 1000

How does alpha affect error bars

alpha <- mean(chains$alpha)
beta <- mean(chains$beta)
gamma <- mean(chains$gamma)
sigma <- mean(chains$sigma)

sigalpha <- sd(chains$alpha)

ameanpred <- sim_mmm_fixedparam(chains,h=h,alpha=alpha,beta=beta,gamma=gamma,sigma=sigma)
apluspred <- sim_mmm_fixedparam(chains,h=h,alpha=alpha+sigalpha,beta=beta,gamma=gamma,sigma=sigma)
aminuspred <- sim_mmm_fixedparam(chains,h=h,alpha=alpha-sigalpha,beta=beta,gamma=gamma,sigma=sigma)
aplus2pred <- sim_mmm_fixedparam(chains,h=h,alpha=alpha+2*sigalpha,beta=beta,gamma=gamma,sigma=sigma)
aminus2pred <- sim_mmm_fixedparam(chains,h=h,alpha=alpha-2*sigalpha,beta=beta,gamma=gamma,sigma=sigma)

Summary

Bayesian forecast is consistent with the optimized ets forecast,

but larger error bars because of averaging over a range of smoothing parameters
